Why not
```suggestion
    HasFPowerSeriesWithinOnBall (fun x i ↦ f i x) (FormalMultilinearSeries.pi p) s e r where
```
? (Many times)

It's on purpose. Both are of course the same for a proficient Lean user, but for newcomers I think my spelling is more readable: you have a function of `x` which turns out to be a function. Since I'm really speaking about the power series structure for `x`, not `i`, I want to emphasize they have different roles.

One more spelling: `fun x ↦ (f · x)`. BTW, new users will probably read docs, where both of the notations above will produce `fun x i ↦ f i x` and `fun x ↦ (f · x)` will produce `fun x x_1 => f x_1 x`. So, no matter which notation you use, if you want to make it readable for newcomers, then please explain the meaning of `fun x i => f i x` in the section docstring.
Is this radius equal to the inf of `(p i).radius`?
Here and below: is it hard to prove the `Iff` version? Am I right that `0 < r` is automatic for nonempty `ι`?

I have proved a few of the iff versions. However, for the last statements (analyticWithinAt and friends), #16752 is needed if I want a very short proof. So you can either merge this one now (and I'll add the missing bits to an API-extending PR which is scheduled after #16752) or merge #16752 now and then I will add the missing bits to the current PR.
